            "detect_impact's seed filter uses .unwrap_or(changed_files): the (unreachable, language=None) error path restores the full seed rather than silently emptying the blast radius — the safe failure direction.",
            "dd132d6's test matrix covers all four quadrants: default excludes data, explicit code_only=false restores inclusion, timestamp and git_ref defaults proven unchanged, and envelope disclosure asserted on the mixed source+data case; tests/detect_impact.rs asserts both the default and the include_data opt-in against a fixture that fails pre-fix (FR-011 honored).",
            "a646f23 did not touch tests/detect_impact.rs (git diff dd132d6..a646f23 empty) and left every dd132d6 test intact; it replaced a weak structural frecency comment-test with a genuine handler-level positive-control test (probe none -> browse -> still none -> get_file_content -> some), a strictly stronger neutrality guarantee.",
            "Browse dedup runs after the include_tests/include_vendor/include_generated classification gates and after the deterministic total-order sort, so the retained representative is always the top-ranked admitted symbol and determinism (Constitution IV) is preserved; a646f23 also updated the search_symbols tool description to disclose the dedup at the MCP schema surface."
          ],
          "summary": "Reviewed committed commits dd132d6 (source-focused defaults for what_changed uncommitted mode and detect_impact) and a646f23 (browse dedup + frecency-neutrality test hardening) against the 018 spec contracts; all cited code read from immutable git objects (dirty working-tree files do not overlap this scope). The core mechanism is sound and well-tested — mode-scoped defaults are consistent between handlers and the disclosure summary, explicit opt-ins are preserved, and dd132d6's regression tests cover default/opt-in/mode-isolation/disclosure. The defects are all on the disclosure and classification edges: detect_impact applies its new default filter with zero response-level or description-level disclosure (an all-config diff now reports '0 changed files' indistinguishably from a clean tree), what_changed's zero-hit reply blames 'requested filters' the caller never requested while its schema docs still advertise the old inclusive default, the code_only classifier over-approximates 'data' as 'any unrecognized extension' so real source classes (.sql, .sh, Dockerfile) silently vanish from default answers, and the 018/015 contract files drifted from a646f23's undocumented browse dedup.",
