              "symbol": "CcrStore::insert",
              "summary": "Duplicate content-addressed inserts double-count total_bytes (and economics.bytes_stored) because HashMap::insert overwrites the existing blob without subtracting its length, permanently inflating the store's accounting and eventually evicting every promised retrieve hash on each new insert.",
              "failure_scenario": "f5cad59 makes store.insert() live on every truncating CCR-eligible call (the old guard suppressed it). An agent re-runs get_repo_map detail='full' on a large repo: the output is identical, mint_handle(tool_name, formatted) yields the identical 48-bit handle, blobs.insert() replaces the entry (map size unchanged) but total_bytes += byte_len again — phantom bytes that evict_oldest can never reclaim (removing the single entry subtracts len once). With a multi-MB repo map repeated over a session, phantom total_bytes crosses max_bytes=32MB; from then on the while-loop at lines 124-130 evicts ALL blobs on every insert (evict_oldest returns false only when empty), so every previously issued 'symforge_retrieve with hash=...' footer dangles and symforge_retrieve answers \"CCR retrieve: unknown or expired hash\" — the footer promised a payload that was already evicted. Before full degeneracy, effective capacity shrinks monotonically, evicting promised hashes far earlier than the 32MB/256-entry contract.",
              "evidence": "git show f5cad59:src/protocol/ccr.rs lines 121-144: `let handle = mint_handle(tool_name, &formatted); ... self.total_bytes = self.total_bytes.saturating_add(byte_len); self.blobs.insert(handle.clone(), CcrBlob {...});` — the return value of blobs.insert (the replaced blob) is discarded, its byte length never subtracted. evict_oldest (lines 163-175) subtracts each entry's len exactly once. mint_handle (lines 179-184) is content-addressed, so identical tool output always collides on the same key. Path made live by this commit's guard change at line 201 (`summary.len() >= full.len()` replacing `summary.len() > max_bytes`).",
              "why_tests_miss": "The new tests T020/T021 (ccr.rs:381-425) each perform at most one insert into a fresh CcrStore; no test inserts the same payload twice, and total_bytes is a private field never asserted. ccr_store_evicts_when_over_budget-style tests exercise distinct payloads only.",
              "minimal_fix": "In CcrStore::insert, account for the replaced entry: `if let Some(old) = self.blobs.insert(handle.clone(), blob) { self.total_bytes = self.total_bytes.saturating_sub(old.formatted_bytes.len()); }` — or short-circuit before eviction: if `self.blobs.contains_key(&handle)`, refresh created_at and return the handle without touching total_bytes/offloads.",
              "confidence": "confirmed"
            },
            {
              "severity": "minor",
              "scope": "committed",
              "file": "src/protocol/ccr.rs",
              "line": 201,
              "symbol": "apply_ccr_overflow",
              "summary": "In the narrow band where the full payload overshoots max_bytes by less than the budget-notice footer (~110 bytes), the guard `summary.len() >= full.len()` returns a TRUNCATED summary with no symforge_retrieve footer and nothing stored — and that summary is strictly larger than the untruncated full payload would have been.",
              "failure_scenario": "get_repo_map full with default budget 16000 tokens (64000 bytes) produces 64050 bytes. enforce_token_budget cuts at the last line boundary to e.g. 63980 bytes and appends the ~110-byte '[truncated] Truncated at ~16000 tokens. Original output is ~16013 tokens; budget is 16000 tokens.' footer → summary = 64090 bytes >= full = 64050 bytes → guard fires → agent receives a response that (a) lost the last ~70 bytes (1-2 real outline lines), (b) carries a truncation notice but NO retrieve handle (blob never stored), and (c) is larger than simply returning the complete 64050-byte payload. Truncation occurred, footer absent — the exact contract this commit was meant to close, unfulfilled at the budget boundary.",
              "evidence": "git show f5cad59:src/protocol/ccr.rs lines 193-203: `let max_bytes = (max_tokens as usize).saturating_mul(4); if full.len() <= max_bytes { return full; } ... if summary.len() >= full.len() { return summary; }`. summary is always truncated here (enforce_token_budget_with_ccr at lines 226-233 only computes it after `result.len() > tokens*4`), and per git show f5cad59:src/protocol/format.rs lines 4785-4800 the summary = line-boundary cut (<= max_bytes) + token_truncation_footer, so summary.len() >= full.len() holds exactly when full_len - truncated_len <= footer_len, i.e. an overshoot smaller than ~110 bytes.",
              "why_tests_miss": "T020 (ccr_footer_emitted_when_builder_truncates) uses full = 74000 bytes against a 1200-byte budget — a huge gap where the guard cannot fire; no test exercises a payload only marginally over max_bytes.",
              "minimal_fix": "In the `summary.len() >= full.len()` branch return `full` instead of `summary`: when the summary saved nothing, the untruncated payload is both smaller and lossless, and no footer is then correct because nothing was cut.",
              "confidence": "confirmed"
            }
          ],
          "summary": "Reviewed committed f5cad59 (emit symforge_retrieve footer when big responses truncate) in src/protocol/ccr.rs and src/protocol/mod.rs against the five assigned checks. The core fix is sound: the guard change makes the CCR footer fire on real truncations, the full pre-truncation payload is stored before the cut and T020 asserts the hash resolves to it, within-budget responses gain no footer (T021), the mod.rs -8 refactor is behavior-equivalent (traced None/Some(0)/normal budgets; only difference is the ccr_store mutex now locks even within budget), the footer legitimately pushes the response ~200 bytes over max_bytes with no loop and no downstream path that re-cuts it, and the line-boundary cut is UTF-8-safe (char_indices, never mid-char). Two defects survive: the now-live CcrStore::insert double-counts total_bytes on duplicate content-addressed inserts, degrading to a store that evicts every promised hash; and a narrow budget-boundary band still truncates without a footer while returning more bytes than the untruncated payload.",
          "verdict": "FINDINGS — the footer contract holds on the main path, but duplicate-insert accounting can invalidate promised hashes and a boundary band still truncates footerless.",
          "positive_evidence": [
